    <room name="D.docs">
    </room>
    <room name="D.embedded">
      <event id="11434">
        <start>13:00</start>
        <duration>01:00</duration>
        <room>D.embedded</room>
        <slug>from_reset_vector_to_kernel</slug>
        <title>From Reset Vector to Kernel</title>
        <subtitle>Navigating the ARM Matryoshka</subtitle>
        <track>Embedded, Mobile and Automotive</track>
        <type>devroom</type>
        <language/>
        <abstract>&lt;p&gt;Long gone are the times of executing the OS in-place from
memory-mapped flash upon reset. A modern SoC now comes with
complex mask ROM firmware, with driver, filesystem, protocol
and crypto support for loading... yet another bootloader.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In his talk, Ahmad follows this chain of bootloaders until
the kernel is started, stopping along the way for RAM setup,
peripherial initialization, runtime services and other interesting sights.&lt;/p&gt;</abstract>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Getting acquainted with the bootstrap process on a modern ARM-based SoC can
be an intimidating task: Documentation speaks of Boot ROM, blobs, SPL,
secure monitor, trusted execution environment, Open Firmware Device Trees
all interacting with each other and with a bootloader to facilitate kernel boot.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The talk intends to shed some light onto this. Starting with an overview
of the bare minimum needed to bootstrap an i.MX8M, it retraces the steps
of the barebox bootloader, and firmware loaded by it, until Linux eventually
takes over.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
        <persons>
          <person id="7326">Ahmad Fatoum</person>
        </persons>
        <attachments>
          <attachment type="slides" href="https://fosdem.org/2021/schedule/event/from_reset_vector_to_kernel/attachments/slides/4632/export/events/attachments/from_reset_vector_to_kernel/slides/4632/from_reset_vector_to_kernel.pdf"/>
        </attachments>
